        <section id="filmmaker-spotlight" class="spotlight-section">
            <h2>Filmmaker Spotlight: Martin Scorsese</h2>
            <div class="spotlight-content">
                <img src="marty.webp" alt="Martin Scorsese" class="movie-poster">
                <p>Martin Scorsese, an iconic figure in American cinema, is renowned for his compelling storytelling, dynamic visual style, and profound explorations of complex characters and themes. Born on November 17, 1942, in New York City, Scorsese's films often reflect his Italian-American heritage and the vibrant, gritty backdrop of mid-20th-century NYC. His work frequently explores themes of identity, guilt, redemption, and the blurred lines between sin and virtue, making his characters deeply flawed yet profoundly relatable.</p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="hobby">
            <h2>Why Movies Are A Great Hobby</h2>
            <p>Movies are not just a source of entertainment; they are a window to different cultures, emotions, and experiences. They inspire creativity, foster empathy by telling stories from diverse perspectives, and serve as a medium for social commentary. As a hobby, watching movies can be both a personal journey and a shared experience, making it uniquely enriching.</p>
        </section>

            <section id="goodfellas" class="film-section">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-gun"></i> Goodfellas (1990)</h2>
                <img src="MCDGOOD_EC028.webp" alt="Goodfellas Poster" class="movie-poster">
                <p>Directed by Martin Scorsese, "Goodfellas" is a thrilling exploration of mob life in New York City. Known for its dynamic narrative and compelling performances.</p>
                <iframe src="𝐈 𝐀𝐋𝐖𝐀𝐘𝐒 𝐖𝐀𝐍𝐓𝐄𝐃 𝐓𝐎 𝐁𝐄 𝐀 𝐆𝐀𝐍𝐆𝐒𝐓𝐄𝐑.mp4"alt= frameborder="0" allowfullscreen class="movie-trailer"></iframe>

                <article id="goodfellas-bts" class="film-section">
                    <h3>Behind the Scenes of Goodfellas</h3>
                    <div class="film-flex-container">

                        <div class="film-item">
                            <img src="Jimmycon - Copy.webp" alt="jimmy1" class="film-image">
                            <p>Jimmy </p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="film-item">
                            <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 154926.png" alt="Henry" class="film-image">
                            <p>Henry</p>
                        </div>

                        <div class="film-item">
                            <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 154857.png" alt="Tommy" class="film-image">
                            <p>Tommy</p>
                        </div>
                    <p id = "paragraph"><em>Goodfellas</em> is acclaimed for its dynamic narrative and immersive storytelling, achieved through innovative cinematography and authentic performances. A key highlight is the "Copacabana Shot," a long, unbroken take that follows Henry Hill through the back entrance of a nightclub. This scene required meticulous planning and execution, highlighting Scorsese's attention to detail and his desire to immerse the audience fully in the film's world.</p><br>
                    <p>Scorsese's use of music in <em>Goodfellas</em> is also noteworthy. He meticulously selected period-specific songs that not only complement the narrative but also enhance the emotional resonance of each scene, effectively using the soundtrack as an additional narrative layer.</p>
                </article>
                
            </section>
            <section id="casino" class="film-section">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-gun"></i> Casino (1995)</h2>
                <img src="Casino-0299.jpg" alt="Casino Movie Poster" class="movie-poster">
                <p>"Casino" delves into the glitz, glamour, and corruption of Las Vegas gambling, crafted masterfully by Scorsese.</p>
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/EJXDMwGWhoA" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen class="movie-trailer"></iframe>
                <article id="casino-bts" class="film-section">
                    <h3>Behind the Scenes of Casino</h3>
                    <div class="film-flex-container">
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 155618.png" alt="ginger" class="film-image">
                        <p>Ginger</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 155636.png" alt="sam" class="film-image">
                        <p>Sam</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 155643.png"nicky=" class="film-image">
                        <p>Nicky</p>
                    </div>
                    <p><em>Casino</em> delves into the glitz and corruption of Las Vegas, with Scorsese using meticulous set designs and costumes to recreate the extravagant world of 1970s and 80s casino life. The film's elaborate sets were constructed to reflect the real-life opulence and excess of the era, with attention paid to even the smallest details to ensure historical accuracy.</p>
                    <p>The film also showcases Scorsese's skill in directing ensemble casts, with dynamic performances from Robert De Niro, Sharon Stone, and Joe Pesci. Stone's preparation for her role involved extensive research into her character's background, resulting in a performance that earned her an Academy Award nomination.</p>
                </article>
                
            </section>

            <section id="american-gangster" class="film-section">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-gun"></i> American Gangster (2007)</h2>
                <img src="Script_Library_-_American_Gangster.webp" alt="American Gangster Movie Poster" class="movie-poster">
                <p>Ridley Scott's Discuss Ridley Scott's direction and Denzel Washington's portrayal of Frank Lucas. Highlight the film's exploration of race, power, and the American justice system.</p>
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/BV_nssS6Zkg" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen class="movie-trailer"></iframe>
                <article id="american-gangster-bts" class="film-section">
                    <h3>Behind the Scenes of American Gangster</h3> 
                    <div class="film-flex-container">
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 161503.png"frank=" class="film-image">
                        <p>Frank</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 161510.png"trupo=" class="film-image">
                        <p>Dectitive Trupo </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 161540.png"Ricky=" class="film-image">
                        <p>Richie</p>
                    </div>
                    <p>Ridley Scott's "American Gangster" presents a meticulous depiction of Frank Lucas' criminal empire and Richie Roberts' pursuit of justice. The film's authenticity was achieved through extensive research and consultation with the real Richie Roberts, ensuring that the portrayal of 1970s Harlem and the heroin trade was as true to life as possible.</p>
                    <p>One of the film's major challenges was recreating the era's setting, requiring detailed set designs, vintage wardrobes, and period-appropriate locations that reflected the gritty atmosphere of the time. Denzel Washington's portrayal of Lucas involved a deep understanding of his complex character, blending charisma with the cold efficiency of a drug lord, achieved through discussions with individuals familiar with Lucas and the period.</p>
                    <p>The film's dynamic between Lucas and Roberts is heightened by Scott's direction, using contrasting visual styles to represent their differing worlds, while the strategic use of music helps anchor the narrative in its time and place, adding depth to the film's historical context.</p>
                </article>
                
            </section>

            <section id="taxi-driver" class="film-section">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-taxi"></i> Taxi Driver (1976)</h2>
                <img src="Taxi_Driver.JPG" alt="Taxi Driver Movie Poster" class="movie-poster">
                <p> Delve into Scorsese and De Niro's examination of urban isolation and moral ambiguity. Discuss the film's iconic status, its influence on cinema, and its controversial themes.</p>
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/UUxD4-dEzn0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen class="movie-trailer"></iframe>
                <article id="taxi-driver-bts" class="film-section">
                    <h3>Behind the Scenes of Taxi Driver</h3>
                    <div class="film-flex-container">
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 162243.png"Travis=" class="film-image">
                        <p>Travis</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 162212.png"Iris=" class="film-image">
                        <p>Iris</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 162122.png"Betty=" class="film-image">
                        <p>Betty</p>
                    </div>
                    <p><em>Taxi Driver</em> remains one of Scorsese's most powerful films, exploring themes of loneliness and violence. The film's climactic shootout scene is particularly famous for its intense, visceral impact. Scorsese and cinematographer Michael Chapman used innovative lighting and camera techniques to create the unsettling, surreal atmosphere that defines the film's aesthetic.</p>
                    <p>Robert De Niro's portrayal of Travis Bickle is deeply influenced by his intense method acting. De Niro famously drove a cab around New York City to prepare for the role, adding a layer of authenticity to his performance that contributes significantly to the film's gritty realism.</p>
                </article>
                
            </section>

            <section id="scarface" class="film-section">
                <h2><i class="fas fa-gun"></i> Scarface (1983)</h2>
                <img src="Scarface-featured-1.webp" alt="Scarface Movie Poster" class="movie-poster">
                <p>Examine Brian De Palma's stylistic choices and Al Pacino's intense performance. Discuss the film's commentary on the American Dream, excess, and immigrant experience.</p>
                <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/cv276Wg3e7I" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen class="movie-trailer"></iframe>
                <article id="scarface-bts" class="film-section">
                    <h3>Behind the Scenes of Scarface</h3>
                    <div class="film-flex-container">
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <section>
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 162634.png"Tony=" class="film-image">
                        <p>Tony</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 162744.png"manny=" class="film-image">
                        <p>Manny</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="film-item">
                        <img src="Screenshot 2024-02-01 162648.png"Elvira=" class="film-image">
                        <p>Elvira</p>
                    </div>
                    <p>"Scarface," directed by Brian De Palma, stands as a monumental film in the crime genre, portraying the relentless ambition of Tony Montana. The film's production is notable for its dedication to authenticity, from the detailed sets that mirrored Miami's 1980s drug scene to the extensive use of live ammunition in some action sequences for realism.</p>
                    <p>The infamous chainsaw scene, one of the film's most intense moments, pushed the boundaries of on-screen violence at the time. De Palma's direction aimed to convey the brutal reality of the drug trade, balancing explicit content with artistic intention. Al Pacino's deep dive into his character involved months of dialect training and mingling with Miami's Cuban community to portray Montana's complex persona convincingly.</p>
                    <p>The film's climactic final shootout required intricate choreography and multiple takes to capture the chaos and violence that culminates Tony's story, showcasing the film crew's commitment to De Palma's visionary direction.</p>

                </article>
            </section>
            
